Abstract

Calculus I: A Manipulatives-Based Approach is a series of eight lesson plans for a high school introductory calculus course. Each lesson plan makes special use of a manipulative: a physical or digital artifact that seeks to demonstrate a keep concept in calculus (as a class activity of teacher demonstration.) The lessons vary from fundamentally teaching topics from different perspectives, to providing simple physical demonstrations for an otherwise traditional calculus lecture. Each lesson plan contains detailed instructions and a slide show for delivering the lesson, homework, student notes outlines, as well as detailed instructions to create the manipulatives. A small set of examples of manipulatives is also included. The lesson plans cover the following topics: 1. Rates of change (using LEGOs), Chain

 

Manipulatives have the potential to not only make calculus more engaging, but increase students understandings of conceptually difficult, abstract ideas. Calculus I: A Manipulatives-Based Approach will discuss eight approaches to incorporating manipulatives into an introductory calculus course, going in depth on one of these lessons.

Introduction

Why Manipulatives[TP2] ?

Manipulatives, generally, are things to be handled by students to enhance learning. In the Encyclopedia of Mathematics Education, mathematical manipulatives are defined as artifacts used in mathematics education: they are handled by students in order to explore, acquire, or investigate mathematical concepts or processes and to perform problem-solving activities drawing on perceptual (visual, tactile, or, more generally, sensory) evidence.[1] This work primarily focuses on concrete (physical) manipulatives, but also includes some virtual (digital) manipulatives, as well as demonstrations for a teacher to perform.

Incorporating manipulatives into the mathematics classroom can provide a wide array of benefits for students, if done in a thoughtful manner. Manipulatives can often be obvious to include in a class. Situations where 3D drawing arise, or animated figures are helpful, there are often simple manipulatives that can be included in a traditional lesson. These can be beneficial because they often provide a better demonstration of the concept being explained, or at the very least provide an alternative way to understand and remember an idea.

Another natural benefit of this approach over traditional lectures is that manipulatives are much more engaging. This is a proven result of effective manipulative use in classrooms, even at the secondary level, where it has been shown not only do these activities increase engagement, but also student attitude.[2] Naturally, there is a relationship between increased engagement due to manipulatives and students problem-solving abilities and academic performance.[3]

Manipulatives are useful for neurodivergent students. This is an exceptionally broad classification, so the reasons will vary student to student, but can include increased benefit from manipulatives due to their increase in engagement and focus [4]. Some neurodivergent students will also benefit from the slower place many manipulative lessons will take, and heightened emphasis on connections between the tangible and abstract. However, for many students with physical disabilities, physical manipulatives can pose a barrier to the same education as their peers. In a survey, special educators overwhelmingly voiced their support (94%) for the use of manipulatives, but cited the need for differentiated options for students who cant interact with them the same way. They emphasized the effectiveness of virtual options [5]. The following lesson plans are primarily (7 of 8) physical manipulatives, but most of these (X[TP3] [TP4]  of 7) have detailed instructions for digital options or use as a demonstration by the instructor rather than activity for all students.

Finally, the primary motivator for manipulatives is to increase learning outcomes for students. A literature review spanning 55 studies implementing mathematical manipulatives from kindergarten to college math classrooms found manipulatives to positively influence retention, problem-solving, transfer, and justification [6]. [TP5] However, these results were moderated by varying instructional techniques, and connections between manipulative and abstract concept.

Accordingly, teachers understanding of manipulatives, and desire to use them significantly impact their effectiveness. Teachers who are informed and excited to use manipulatives have found them effective, especially for struggling students, whereas teachers who view them as toys or distractions do not benefit. [7] Interviews have also revealed that a significant number of math teachers recognize the potential for manipulatives to have positive impacts on their classes, but lack the mathematical background, pedagogical background, resources, or confidence to properly implement manipulatives [8] Since there have been shown to be many benefits of using manipulatives, but teacher knowledge can hinder these effects, each lesson plan includes an introduction with the pedagogical backing for the manipulative, as well as detailed instructions on the creation and use in a class setting.

Why Calculus?

Calculus was chosen for this project for several reasons. Calculus is a common math course, in post-secondary as well as advanced secondary settings. Unfortunately, calculus, especially the first calculus course in a series, is often exceptionally difficult for students, due to a variety of factors, from courses covering too much content, to systemic issues for minority background students. [9] It also represents a paradigm shift in mathematical thinking towards more abstract, dynamic topics, which can feel less given to physical manipulatives. This factor, in addition to the accelerated nature of calculus courses leave little thought or time for incorporating manipulatives into calculus courses. However, there have been a handful of educators to do so on larger scales.

One study on the effectiveness of manipulatives in calculus was conducted in 2016, working with honors, AP AB, and AP BC calculus students. Similar lessons to the lessons presented here were used, including box folding optimization, revolving solids, and cutting out curves. However, the execution and intent vary significantly in each lesson. The study found the experimental (manipulatives) group of students exhibited a significantly higher level of learning gain. Additionally, a majority of students reported their learning was enhanced. Even among students who did not report positively, most stated the manipulatives boosted their engagement, and none reported negatively. The teacher also reported positively on the manipulatives. After initial hesitation due to the extra time required, they believed that it ultimately was worthwhile, keeping students motivated and providing deeper understanding for many. [10]

While Rivero has collected a small series of manipulative lessons for introductory calculus, there have been few efforts to thoroughly center a curriculum around manipulatives in the subject. At Harvard University, Janet Chen and Stepan Paul have developed a series of lessons for Harvards Math 21a Multivariable Calculus course, primarily revolving around 3D printing. As of the Fall 2019 semester, they have begun creating models and lessons for Math 1b Integral Calculus, but as of February 2024, there is only one lesson publicly available (solids of revolution) [11]. In 2022, Make: Community, a 3D printing book and magazine publisher, published Make: Calculus, which is a wonderful collection of 3D printing (and other manipulative format) projects. They are wonderful demonstrations that illustrate the beauty of calculus but are less intended to teach formal calculus methods and more so to expose readers to the essence of the principles of calculus [12] So, to my knowledge, there is no large collection of calculus 1 manipulative lesson plans currently available online, which calls for these to be created.

Personal Motivation

The final motivation for centering this project on introductory calculus is personal. In high school, I had a mediocre experience in calculus the class was highly traditional. All instruction was dry lectures at a whiteboard, and there were no opportunities to apply what we learned, or options to learn in different formats. However, in spite of this, I was able to grasp the beauty of calculus through online resources, like the online video series The Essence of Calculus, which was being released as I was in my first calculus class. [13] Unknowingly hindered by learning disabilities in my high school classroom, the clear, visual demonstrations of calculus ideas in these videos and other similar ones motivated me to pursue math in college.

Since graduating high school, Ive gone on to teach and tutor students from diverse backgrounds in math through a different medium in a variety of subjects, calculus chief among them. It didnt take me long working with calculus students to realize many of them struggle in the same ways I did to conceptualize these new, abstract concepts. I found myself referring them to the essence of calculus series frequently. I also would create mini, ad hoc hands-on artifacts to illustrate concepts. These include programming the streetlight problem in GeoGebra, using unifix cubes to show change in a function and area under a curve, cutting out curves to help students feel the derivative, and even once trying to sculpt a solid of revolution out of wet sand from a playground.

After having these opportunities to work with students, I was inspired to pursue the teachers license in mathematics at Carleton and St. Olaf colleges. The idea of being able to share with students the beauty of math and calculus is quite exciting to me, so the opportunity to create a comps project I will directly be able to use and test in my career was perfect. My goal is to go on to teach calculus at the secondary level, and implement these lesson plans. I hope to receive feedback from students, make the necessary adjustments and ultimately publish them in some form to make this style of teaching more widely available to calculus teachers.

What is in a Lesson [TP6] Plan?

Each chapter in this series contains three main parts: the introduction, the lesson plan, and formative assessment. Some may contain optional extensions or alterations, and appendices. Each chapter has an associated slide show, as well as a student note outline. (Not included in this document see [ ] to access.)

The introduction provides a big picture overview of the lesson, as well as pedagogical background as needed.

The lesson plan contains all the typical aspects of a lesson plan. It begins by stating the topic of the lesson, and learning objectives, stated in the standard Students Will Be Able To (SWBAT) format. Following the objectives is the lesson outline. This section provides a structure for a teacher to use, teaching their class this lesson. Specific details about what should be lecture/examples/group work/omitted have been left out, as these lesson plans are intended to be as general as possible for use in a variety of classes. Changes should be made to match the specific needs of classes and students. Following the lesson sequence, there is a lesson summary, containing the key points students should be taking away from the lesson.

The final aspect is a set of formative assessment questions. These can be used as exit slips or assigned as homework. Again, modification is encouraged. Some questions are sampled out of the Strang Calculus textbook, which is available free of charge from the University of Minnesota Center for Open Education. [14] Exit slips can also be created. For reference, here is an example for the related rates lesson:

Question

Answer

My group completed the in class problems successfully

In some chapters, extensions, suggestions, and modifications also follow. Review these and apply as necessary depending on class needs.

Some chapters also have an associated appendix. These sections contain detailed instructions for the creation of certain manipulatives. They are not included in the lesson plan due to their complexity and lack of educational value in completing them as a class but are not difficult to create following these provided instructions.

Some Motivation: Discuss what change means, in a very general way. What are some ways change can be measured? What are some examples of changes we can measure? This is a primary concern of calculus if we can measure something, and can predict it with a mathematical function, we will also know how much it is changing at any given point in time. E.g., interest in a bank account, height of a projectile, chemical reactions, a cars speed, etc.

Changes in Math (Review of algebra): A change between two points is measured by dividing the rise (change in height) over run (change in width). rise over run.

Manipulatives: Give each student 15 LEGO 2x2 bricks, and a base plate. [TP8] Allow them to build any shape they want, but are restricted to 2D structures (i.e., all their bricks must fall in one row:). They can get creative! Even going off the ends of the base plate is permissible, as long as all the bricks are properly connected together.

After a few minutes, every student should have a shape they are happy with. E.g., . Now, each student picks two points on their structure, A and B. Ensure B is to the right and above A, in the first example. They can be labeled with marks with dry erase markers, placing the figure on a blank piece of paper and using a pencil, using a different colored brick, or just remembered.

How can the change between these two points be measured? How can we calculate the rate of change? Find the rise (in number of bricks) and the run (in number of pegs)! In this example, with a rise of 4 and run of 14, this gives us a slope of 4/14 (model rises 4/14ths of a brick per 1 peg it runs, on average, between these two points. This is how fast upwards my structure is growing!

Is my model growing this fast everywhere? Repeat the process of finding the slope with two different points. This example illustrates how when the rise is really a fall, its a negative slope, since we are thinking about what we need to add to point A to get to B, but to get down, well need to add a negative number. (Slope = rise/run = -2/5)

Practice Time: In base groups, students should work together to find different slopes a[TP9] 


 

2.    Derivatives: Chain Rule and Function Composition with Paper [TP10] Bags[TP11] 

Function Composition

2.1      Introduction

Differentiating between function multiplication and function composition can be a difficult concept for many students in an introductory calculus task. By creating a novel manipulative, this difference will become more cemented, and students will build a stronger sense of what is actually happening when functions are composed. This lesson serves as a hands-on introduction to the chain rule taking derivatives of composite functions. This lesson was inspired by a paper [15] and presentation given at the JMM in 2012.

3.    Related Rates: Interactive Applications

3.1      Introduction

This project aims to create an example of creating a visual, manipulable demonstration for a common related rates problem (as many have before, in various mediums: [17] [18], even other examples from Stewart: [19].) This particular question, about how fast someones shadow moves as they walk past a light pole, is a classic related rates problem. It also poses many of the classic difficulty students have with this type of problem: it is easily described in an overly vague way. This leads students either fail to understand what a problem is asking, leaving them confused, or improperly understanding the problem. It is hard to fault the student in many of these cases it is difficult to picture how fast the tip of your shadow moves as you walk past a light pole. In this example, seeing the actual movement helps remove the possibility of common errors in different interpretations of a problem statement. It also allows students to see the underlying relationships better after teaching this problem for two years, I have still struggled to articulate that the person moving moves the tip of the shadow, as well as the shadow elongating. Oftentimes, students will take my word for it, clearly not understanding the point Im trying to convey. When set up correctly, like in this case, these demonstrations can also better illustrate the underlying background knowledge at play (in this case, similar triangles.) This also happens in a satisfying, dynamic way, illustrating the permanence of the relationship in the problem. Manipulatives like this can be used in a lecture as a demonstration to clarify what a problem is asking, or students can also use them on their individual devices.

4.    Optimization: The Masu Box

4.1      Introduction

Kazuo Haga describes the intersection of origami and mathematics as origamics. [24] There are countless applications of calculus in origami, and we will use it in this lesson to optimize the area of a simple paper box. Not only will this give students hands-on practice with an optimization problem, but it will also teach them a fun skill in origami and expose them to an ancient Chinese artform[TP20] .

Many optimization problems students will be exposed to in textbooks like Stewart and Strang can feel contrived, and hard to visualize, much like the related rates problems. This lesson gives students a break from a fast-paced, abstract curriculum to engage in a fun, artistic activity, with a calculus problem appended midway through.

This lesson was inspired by a chapter [25] in the conference proceedings of the International Meeting of Origami Science, Mathematics, and Education [26]. For a similar lesson, see [27].

5.    Derivatives: Review of Common Functions using Construction Paper

5.1      Introduction[TP22] [TP23] 

For those comfortable with calculus, the idea of the derivative is quite intuitive it is the rate of change of its input function. Student learning derivatives for the first time will also know this fact, but in practice, frequently get tripped up by determining which way up is, or situations like where a function is negative, but has a positive derivative.

This lesson is intended as a way to help a class review common functions and their derivatives. Optionally, it can easily be extended to cover integrals as well. Since, unlike other lessons in this series, it is not intended to introduce new material, its placement in a curriculum is quite flexible. I believe it makes the most sense after introducing a class to common derivatives (e.g., trig, power rule, etc.), but before introducing more advanced derivative techniques (e.g., chain rule, product rule). It can also be taught before common derivatives are formally introduced, as this lessons main purpose is to cement students conceptual understanding of the derivative, and solidify the notion that the slope, not the sign, of the function determines its derivative.

There are a variety of ways to implement these manipulatives. Most simply, the teacher can print a few graphs and assemble them before class for students to use. The assembly is quite straightforward and intuitive, so it is an appropriate project for students to construct in a short class period. One option for this is to assign each student a common function (and its derivative), teach the class the assembly, and work together to create a class set.

The main objective with these manipulatives, once created, is to cement the feeling of the derivative: trace your finger along the function curve, from left to right. When your finger goes up, look at the derivative function it should be positive, above the x-axis regardless of if f is positive or negative. When your finger moves down, regardless of its position with respect to the x-axis, the derivative is negative. When the derivative changes from positive to negative, your finger shouldve went over a bump, or high point: it was going uphill, but now, its going downhill.

For people comfortable with calculus, this is intuitive. Some may even call it obvious. But for first time learners, it can be incredibly difficult to understand this fundamental relationship between these two curves. A primary struggle with this is divorcing their mind from thinking about the sign of the function, just its slope. This is difficult because, of course, the slope of the function is what determines the sign of the derivative, so disregarding the information that can feel so important in the function is difficult, especially when these pieces of information (and noninformation) contradict themselves.

This lesson was loosely inspired by Horvath and Camerons Make: Calculus, where 3D printing technology was used to create a similar effect. [29]

6.    Fundamental Theorem with LEGOs

6.1      Introduction

The Fundamental Theorem of Calculus is a beautiful and key aspect of calculus, and nicely bridges the gap between learning about derivatives and learning about integrals. Introducing this concept with manipulatives instead of a basic lecture will help students understand the concept better and give them a greater appreciation of the beauty of calculus, as opposed to a traditional lesson encouraging rote memorization.[TP24] 

This lesson can be taught as a traditional introduction to the fundamental theorem, concluding derivatives and beginning integrals in an introductory course. Alternatively, it can be taught after a conceptual introduction to derivatives, to give students a taste of the beauty of calculus.

8.    Solids of Revolution with Disks using 3D Printed Models[TP32] 

8.1      Introduction[TP33] 

Solids of Revolution, [TP34] much like cross-sectional area, is a topic plagued by math teachers collective overconfidence in their ability to draw 3D shapes on the 2D chalk or white board. (Or, teachers admit they arent artists, but fail to create any better representation of these figures than mediocre-at-best drawings.) Naturally, this can be a big barrier for students. Even using graphical software to render accurate projections onto 2D projector screens or textbook pages still lacks a certain This lesson aims to address this issue by providing easy to create models of several common solids that can be inserted into most preexisting lectures.

In fact, 3D printing methods have been shown to be effective for increasing student outcomes. In middle school classrooms in Trkiye, 3D models were shown not only to improve test scores, but student confidence and ability to visualize 3D shapes. [32] In university-level multivariable calculus courses, it was shown that 3D printed manipulatives boosted grades by 7% and the passage rate for a spatial skills test increased 36%. [33] Due to these methods proven effectiveness, and this being a difficult area for many students, this lesson plan demonstrates simple 3D printed manipulatives embedded in a traditional solids of revolutions class.

9.    Appendix X: Folding the masu box

9.1      Folding standard masu box

1.      Start with square paper on flat surface.

2.      Fold upper left and lower right corners together.

3.      Unfold.

4.      Fold remaining corners together.

5.      Unfold.

6.      Fold all corners to center.

7.      Fold opposite edges to center crease.

8.      Unfold.

9.      Repeat folding remaining edges to center crease.

10. Unfold.

11. Unfold two of the original corners.

12. Fold down the very top and very bottom crease.

13. While folding flap up (crease along very bottom), form triangle folds inside the flap.

14. Fold flap over edge, and crease end of flap along bottom of box.

15. Repeat on opposite side.

16. Fold over last flap, creasing its end along bottom edge of box.

17. Masu box complete!

Thanks to Mark Kirschenbaum for the basis for these instructions! [36]

9.2      Folding masu boxes of varied height

1.      Repeat {7}.[TP35] 1 steps 1 through 6

2.    Measure the edge to find . (using 15cm2 paper, this should yield a length of slightly more than )

3.    Make marks from each edge (in this case, we are constructing the masu box, yielding marks at from each edge)

4.      Repeat for the three remaining edges. Optionally, lines can be drawn in connecting points straight across)

5.      Fold two opposite edges to points/lines (note this varies from standard masu box, where this fold is made to center crease)

6.      Repeat for remaining two edges

7.      Repeat steps 11-17 from the standard box to complete!

3.      Add to graph → Surface of Revolution.

4.      Enter equations, bounds, and revolve.

a.      Determine the function(s) being revolved, in terms of x or y, depending on axis.

b.      Check box. Enter the upper equation and lower equation in terms of appropriate variable. Note that for disk revolutions, the lower equation will just be the equation for the axis of revolution (x-axis: y=0 or y-axis: x=0)

c.      Enter the axis of revolution (x-axis: y=0 or y-axis: x=0)

d.      Enter the bounds

e.      Optionally for demonstration, this illustrates a Riemann rectangle that is being integrated

f.        Rotate the region: drag slider all the way to the right for a full revolution. For demonstration or to generate partial rotations, slide part way.


Default curve generated.

5.      The surface has now been generated! It can be spun around in 3D space to demonstrate. If it looks choppy, dont worry, the slicer will smooth out the rectangles.

6.      Now, we can export the shape. Navigate: ≡ → File → Create STL file from the plot

7.      The following menu should open:

a.      Name your solid something descriptive, like the function(s) used to create it and the axis.

b.      The default dimensions and thickness should be OK, but adjust if needed (dimensions can also be adjusted in the slicer)

c.      Create file. Save to computer in reasonable location

8.      Open Prusa Slicer.

9.      Ctrl+I and select STL file created in step 7

10. Solid should appear in Prusa Slicer

11. Place face on print surface: press F, and click on the face of the solid that should sit on the print plate

12. Fix errors

Right-click on the attention symbol (if it shows up). Windows repair should resolve the errors.

13. Your figure is now ready to slice and print. The following steps will vary depending on 3D printers and your specific needs, so consult resources pertaining to your specific setup to complete the process.
